@hachikuji 
I added "status.storage.topic" to DistributedConfig;
@ewencp 
It's great if it can be merged : )

@hachikuji I will go ahead and create the KIP documentation for this. It's a minor change but still worth discussing with a wider audience.

I implemented an equivalent "fair" assignor for the new consumer last night (https://github.com/apache/kafka/pull/979). For that pull request I added a new test (testMultipleConsumersUnbalancedSubscriptions) for each of the 3 implementations, that illustrates the skewed assignments for the range and roundrobin assignors with a borderline worst-case scenario.

For the new consumer we could certainly include a custom implementation in our own code if the KIP gets rejected. In that case I think we should at least document somewhere that the roundrobin assignor can give somewhat suboptimal results if the subscriptions are not identical (which is/will be allowed as of https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-2172).

@ymatsuda Right now we have two rounds for create topics:

1) before calling partition grouper, create topics for internal source topics according to the logic above;

2) after calling partition grouper, create / update topics for changelog and internal source topics.

So we do not need to rely on broker side `auto.create.topics.enable` config.

@gwenshap Thinking about this more, I'm worried that with this change we don't make sure we read to the end of the log at least once before rejoining the group. On initial startup, the DistributedHerder makes sure we've read to the end of the log (we should probably discuss whether the way it does this synchronously with indefinite timeouts is also a problem). But in the failure case now, we may fail to read to log end, hit the timeout, leave the group, and then won't the subsequent tick immediately rejoin the group despite not having read to the end of the log? Seems like this will result in flapping membership in the group if the config topic can't be properly consumed.

So now this is making me think that the `readConfigToEnd` might not even be in the right place to handle this case. Maybe it should be another phase in `tick()` that comes first, controlled by a flag like the `needsReadToEnd` in `handleRebalanceCompleted` but is saved in the instances state so it continues to be attempted even if it continues to fail due to timeouts.

I'm also beginning to think it might be time to create a state diagram for this -- it seems to be pretty complicated...
